article.headline: Abram's 16 helps end two-game skid
article.linkText: Wolverines help case with rout of Penn State
article.story: ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Lester Abram scored 16 points to lead Michigan to a 76-53 win over Penn State on Wednesday. The win ended the Wolverines (14-8, 5-6 Big Ten) two-game losing streak. Marlon Smith scored 19 points for the Nittany Lions (9-13, 3-8), who have lost five straight and are winless in four conference road games this season. The Wolverines, who led 35-27 at halftime, pulled away early in the second half with a 20-4 run. Abram scored nine points during the spurt. Penn State, which used only seven players until late in the game, connected on just 35 percent of its field-goal attempts and turned the ball over 16 times. Bernard Robinson Jr. added 11 points, eight assists and three steals for Michigan, which also got 13 points from Courtney Sims and 11 from Daniel Horton. Aaron Johnson had 11 for Penn State. The win in the first of four straight home games kept alive Michigan's slim hopes for an at-large bid to the NCAA tournament. Its next two contests are visits from Big Ten leaders Wisconsin and Michigan State. <
